=========================================
C++ STL VECTOR – FINAL INTERVIEW MASTER NOTES
=========================================

1. What is vector?
- std::vector is a dynamic array (STL container)
- Stores elements in contiguous memory (like array)
- Provides O(1) random access
- Automatically manages memory (heap-based)

-----------------------------------------

2. Why vector?
- C-style array = fixed size ❌
- vector = dynamic size ✔
- No manual memory management (no new/delete)
- Safe + STL-compatible

-----------------------------------------

3. Internal working (VERY IMPORTANT)
Vector maintains:
- pointer to heap memory
- size (current elements)
- capacity (allocated memory)

When capacity is full:
1. Allocate new memory (usually 2x growth)
2. Move/Copy elements
3. Delete old memory
4. Insert new element

👉 This process = RELOCATION / REALLOCATION

-----------------------------------------

4. Size vs Capacity (MOST ASKED)

size():
- number of elements present

capacity():
- total allocated memory

Rules:
- size <= capacity
- capacity changes only on reallocation

-----------------------------------------

5. reserve vs resize

reserve(n):
- increases capacity only
- size unchanged

resize(n):
- changes size
- adds/removes elements

-----------------------------------------

6. push_back vs emplace_back (VERY IMPORTANT)

push_back:
- inserts object (copy/move happens)

emplace_back:
- constructs object directly in memory
- avoids extra copy/move (more efficient)

-----------------------------------------

7. Iterator invalidation (CRITICAL)

Invalid when:
- reallocation occurs
- insert/erase shifts elements

👉 After reallocation: ALL iterators, pointers, references become invalid

-----------------------------------------

8. Complexity (VERY IMPORTANT)

- operator[] / at()   : O(1)
- push_back          : amortized O(1)
- insert/erase mid   : O(n)
- search             : O(n)

Why amortized O(1)?
- reallocation is rare due to geometric growth

-----------------------------------------

9. at() vs operator[]

operator[]:
- no bounds check (fast, unsafe)

at():
- bounds check (safe, throws exception)

-----------------------------------------

10. clear vs shrink_to_fit

clear():
- removes elements
- size = 0
- capacity unchanged

shrink_to_fit():
- requests memory reduction (not guaranteed)

-----------------------------------------

11. copy vs move vector

copy:
- O(n), copies all elements

move:
- O(1), transfers ownership of memory

-----------------------------------------

12. Contiguous memory (IMPORTANT)

- elements stored in continuous memory
- benefits:
  ✔ fast iteration
  ✔ cache friendly
  ✔ pointer arithmetic works
  ✔ C API compatibility (via data())

-----------------------------------------

13. data()

- returns pointer to underlying array
- useful for C APIs

-----------------------------------------

14. swap()

- swaps two vectors in O(1)
- only pointer exchange happens

-----------------------------------------

15. Vector vs List (COMMON QUESTION)

vector:
- contiguous memory
- fast access O(1)
- cache friendly

list:
- node-based
- slow traversal
- high memory overhead

👉 vector preferred in most cases

-----------------------------------------

16. Ways to initialize vector

- vector<int> v = {1,2,3};
- vector<int> v(n, value);
- vector<int> v(arr, arr+n);
- vector<int> v(other.begin(), other.end());

-----------------------------------------

17. Reallocation details

When push_back causes overflow:
- new memory allocated (usually 2x)
- elements moved/copied
- old memory freed
- iterators invalidated

-----------------------------------------

18. Why push_back is amortized O(1)

- most insertions are O(1)
- occasional O(n) reallocation
- average cost per insertion = O(1)

-----------------------------------------

19. Vector of objects (IMPORTANT)

During reallocation:
- copy constructor or move constructor called
- old objects destroyed
- move preferred over copy

-----------------------------------------

